{{Infobox person | name = Lucy R. Lippard | image = | caption = | birth_date = April 14, 1937 | birth_place = [[New York City]]<ref>[http://arthistorians.info/lippardl Biography at arthistorians.info]</ref> | nationality = American | spouse = | awards = Guggenheim Fellowship (1968), CAA Frank Jewett Mather Award for Criticism (1975), CAA Distinguished Feminist Award (2012), CAA Distinguished Lifetime Achievement Award for Writing on Art (2015) }}
'''Lucy Lippard''' (born April 14, 1937) is an American writer, [[art critic]], [[activist]] and [[curator]]. Lippard was among the first writers to recognize the "[[Dematerialisation (art)|dematerialization]]" at work in [[conceptual art]] and was an early champion of [[feminist art]]. She is the author of 21 books on [[contemporary art]] and has received numerous awards and accolades from literary critics and art associations.
== Early life and education == Lucy Lippard was born in New York City and lived in [[New Orleans, Louisiana|New Orleans]] and [[Charlottesville, Virginia]], before enrolling at [[Abbot Academy]] in 1952. She attended [[Smith College]] and earned a B.A. in 1958. In 1962, she earned an M.A. degree in art history from the [[Institute of Fine Arts]] at [[New York University]].<ref name="OTIS">{{cite web|url=http://www.otis.edu/press-release/pioneering-author-activist-critic-curator-lucy-lippard-to-receive-honorary-degree|title=Pioneering Author, Activist, Critic, and Curator Lucy Lippard to Receive Honorary Degree|website=OTIS College of Art and Design|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>
Just out of college, Lippard began working in the library at the Museum of Modern Art in 1958 where, in addition to reshelving the library after a fire, she was "farmed out" to do research for curators.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=A Brief History of Curating|last=Obrist|first=Hans Ulrich|publisher=JRP Ringier|year=2008|isbn=9783905829556|location=Zurich|pages=}}</ref> She credits these years of working at MoMA paging, filing and researching as preparing her "well for the archival, informational aspect of conceptual art."<ref name=":1" /> At MoMA she worked with curators such as Bill Lieberman, Bill Seitz and Peter Selz.<ref name=":0" /> By 1966, she had curated two traveling exhibitions for MoMA, one on "soft sculpture" and one on Max Ernst, as well as worked with Kynaston McShine on ''Primary Structures'' before he was hired by the Jewish Museum, taking the show with him.<ref name=":0" /> It was at MoMA that Lippard met Sol LeWitt who was working the night desk; John Button, Dan Flavin, Al Held, and Robert Ryman all held positions at the museum during this time as well.<ref name=":0" />
== Career == Since 1966, Lippard has published 20 books—including one novel—on feminism, art, politics and place.<ref name="OTIS" /> She has received numerous awards and accolades from literary critics and art associations.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}} A 2012 exhibition on her seminal book, ''Six Years: The Dematerialization of the Art Object'' at the Brooklyn Museum, titled ''"Six Years": Lucy R. Lippard and the Emergence of Conceptual Art"'', cites Lippard's scholarship as its point of entry into a discussion about conceptual art during its era of emergence, demonstrating her crucial role in the contemporary understanding of this period of art production and criticism.<ref>''[http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/exhibitions/six_years/ "Six Years": Lucy R. Lippard and the Emergence of Conceptual Art"]''</ref> Her research on the move toward [[Dematerialization (art)|Dematerialization]] in art making has formed a cornerstone of contemporary art scholarship and discourse.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}} Lucy Lippard was a member of the populist political artist group known as the [[Art Workers' Coalition|Art Workers Coalition]], or AWC. Her involvement in the AWC as well as a trip she took to Argentina—such trips bolstered the political motivations of many feminists of the time—influenced a change in the focus of her criticism, from formalist subjects to more feministic ones.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Art Workers : Radical Practice in the Vietnam War Era |last=Bryan-Wilson |first=Julia |publisher=University of California Press |year=2009 |isbn= |location=Berkeley and Los Angeles |pages=129}}</ref>
Co-founder of [[Printed Matter, Inc]] (an art bookstore in New York City centered on [[artist's books]]), the [[Heresies Collective]], [[Political Art Documentation/Distribution (PAD/D)]], Artists Call Against U.S. Intervention in Central America, and other artists' organizations, she has also curated over 50 exhibitions, done performances, comics, [[guerrilla theater]], and edited several independent publications the latest of which is the decidedly local ''La Puente de Galisteo'' in her home community in [[Galisteo, New Mexico]].<ref name="AAA">[http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/lucy-r-lippard-papers-7895/more Finding Aid to the Lucy R. Lippard Papers, 1940s-2006], Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution. Retrieved 4 Nov 2013.</ref> She has infused [[aesthetics]] with politics, and disdained disinterestedness for ethical activism.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}}
=== Selected honors and awards === Lippard holds nine honorary doctorates of fine arts,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thenewpress.com/authors/lucy-r-lippard|title=Lucy R. Lippard {{!}} The New Press|work=The New Press|access-date=2018-03-29|language=en}}</ref> of which some are listed below.
*2015: Distinguished Lifetime Achievement Award for Writing on Art, [[College Art Association]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.collegeart.org/programs/awards/writing|title=Awards for Distinction {{!}} Programs {{!}} CAA|last=Association|first=College Art|website=www.collegeart.org|language=en|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> * 2013: Honorary doctorate, [[Otis College of Art and Design]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.otis.edu/honorary-degrees|title=Honorary Degrees|website=Otis College of Art and Design|language=en|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> * 2013: Distinguished critic lecture, [[International Association of Art Critics]], United States<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hyperallergic.com/91190/why-lucy-lippard-never-gets-writers-block/|title=Why Lucy Lippard Never Gets Writer's Block|date=2013-10-31|work=Hyperallergic|access-date=2018-04-05|language=en-US}}</ref> * 2012: Distinguished Feminist Award, [[College Art Association]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.collegeart.org/programs/awards/feminist|title=Awards for Distinction {{!}} Programs {{!}} CAA|last=Association|first=College Art|website=www.collegeart.org|language=en|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> * 2010: Award for Curatorial Excellence, [[Center for Curatorial Studies and Art in Contemporary Culture|Center for Curatorial Studies]], [[Bard College]] * 2007: Honorary Doctor of Fine Arts, ''honoris causa'', [[Nova Scotia College of Art and Design]] (NSCAD University) * 1976: National Endowment for the Arts grant<ref name="AAA" /> * 1975: [[Frank Jewett Mather]] Award for Criticism, [[College Art Association]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.collegeart.org/programs/awards/mather|title=Awards for Distinction {{!}} Programs {{!}} CAA|last=Association|first=College Art|website=www.collegeart.org|language=en|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> * 1972: National Endowment for the Arts grant * 1968: [[Guggenheim Fellowship]]
