{{inline|date=February 2017}} [[File:Tábara Torre 20080906.jpg|thumb|right|[[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] tower of the monastery.]] '''San Salvador de Tábara Monastery''' is a monastery in the present-day town of [[Tábara]] in [[Spain]]. It was founded at the end of the 9th century after [[Alfonso III of Asturias]]'s victory at the [[battle of Polvoraria]].
Its 12th century tower survives. It is notable as the home of the [[scriptorium]] which produced the [[Tábara Beatus]], [[Morgan Beatus]] and [[Gerona Beatus]].
==Sources== *Carlos R. Lafora, ''Andanzas en torno al legado mozárabe'', Ediciones Encuentro, Madrid, 1991, p. 105-107.
